1
00:00:02,085 --> 00:00:06,757
# Her face was like a winter moon

2
00:00:06,840 --> 00:00:11,512
# That lights the traveller's way

3
00:00:11,887 --> 00:00:16,850
# Her smile was like a summer bloom

4
00:00:16,934 --> 00:00:21,355
# That bursts then fades away

5
00:00:21,980 --> 00:00:26,818
# My love is night, my love is day

6
00:00:26,944 --> 00:00:31,823
# My love, she is my world #

7
00:00:31,907 --> 00:00:35,494
Such sweet music
shows your blood to be afire.

8
00:00:35,619 --> 00:00:38,455
Why wait we
on stale custom for consummation?

9
00:00:38,539 --> 00:00:40,958
Oh, yes! Tonight's the night.

10
00:00:47,297 --> 00:00:50,175
Would you enter, bold sir?

11
00:00:50,300 --> 00:00:52,135
Oh, I would.

12
00:00:56,640 --> 00:01:00,811
Lilith, this cannot be
the home of one so beautiful.

13
00:01:01,520 --> 00:01:04,106
Forgive me, this is foul.

14
00:01:04,189 --> 00:01:05,983
Shh.

15
00:01:06,066 --> 00:01:08,986
Sad words suit not
upon a lover's tongue.

16
00:01:15,659 --> 00:01:18,036
Your kiss transformed me.

17
00:01:18,161 --> 00:01:21,164
A suitor should meet
his beloved's parents.

18
00:01:21,290 --> 00:01:23,166
Mother Doomfinger.

19
00:01:25,919 --> 00:01:28,255
And Mother Bloodtide.

20
00:01:28,338 --> 00:01:30,340
(CACKLING)

21
00:01:35,220 --> 00:01:37,931
(SCREAMING)

22
00:01:41,101 --> 00:01:44,688
Soon, at the hour of woven words,

23
00:01:44,813 --> 00:01:49,860
we shall rise again
and this fleeting Earth will perish!

24
00:01:53,363 --> 00:01:55,574
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

25
00:02:32,194 --> 00:02:34,196
(RUMBLING)

26
00:02:34,279 --> 00:02:36,990
But how do you travel in time?
What makes it go?

27
00:02:37,074 --> 00:02:39,326
Oh, let's take the fun
and the mystery out of everything.

28
00:02:39,409 --> 00:02:43,330
Martha, you don't want to know.
It just does. Hold on tight!

29
00:02:45,916 --> 00:02:48,502
Blimey! Do you have to pass a test
to fly this thing?

30
00:02:48,585 --> 00:02:51,296
Yes, and I failed.
Now, make the most of it.

31
00:02:51,380 --> 00:02:53,674
I promised you one trip
and one trip only.

32
00:02:53,757 --> 00:02:55,842
Outside this door,

33
00:02:56,802 --> 00:02:58,220
brave new world.

34
00:02:58,303 --> 00:03:00,305
Where are we?

35
00:03:00,389 --> 00:03:02,391
Take a look.

36
00:03:03,100 --> 00:03:04,768
After you.

37
00:03:11,566 --> 00:03:13,610
Oh, you're kidding me.

38
00:03:13,694 --> 00:03:15,737
You're so kidding me!

39
00:03:15,821 --> 00:03:19,282
Oh, my God, we did it!
We travelled in time!

40
00:03:21,451 --> 00:03:23,745
Where are we? No, sorry.

41
00:03:23,829 --> 00:03:27,541
Got to get used to
this whole new language. When are we?

42
00:03:27,624 --> 00:03:30,168
-Mind out.
-Garde a I'eau!

43
00:03:30,293 --> 00:03:34,131
Somewhere before the invention
of the toilet. Sorry about that.

44
00:03:34,256 --> 00:03:37,676
I've seen worse.
I worked the late-night shift, A&E.

45
00:03:37,801 --> 00:03:41,388
But are we safe?
I mean, can we move around and stuff?

46
00:03:41,471 --> 00:03:44,099
-Of course we can. Why do you ask?
-It's like in the films.

47
00:03:44,182 --> 00:03:47,561
You step on a butterfly,
you change the future of the human race.

48
00:03:47,644 --> 00:03:50,105
Tell you what, then.
Don't step on any butterflies.

49
00:03:50,230 --> 00:03:52,524
What have butterflies ever done to you?

50
00:03:52,607 --> 00:03:54,735
What if... I don't know.

51
00:03:54,818 --> 00:03:57,571
-What if I kill my grandfather?
-Are you planning to?

52
00:03:57,654 --> 00:03:59,322
-No.
-Well, then.

53
00:04:00,282 --> 00:04:02,659
-And this is London?
-Think so.

54
00:04:02,743 --> 00:04:06,371
Round about, um, ooh, 1599.

55
00:04:06,872 --> 00:04:09,291
Oh, but hold on. Am I all right?

56
00:04:09,374 --> 00:04:11,501
I'm not going to get carted off
as a slave, am I?

57
00:04:11,626 --> 00:04:12,919
Why would they do that?

58
00:04:13,044 --> 00:04:15,005
Not exactly white,
in case you haven't noticed.

59
00:04:15,130 --> 00:04:17,924
I'm not even human. Just walk about
like you own the place. Works for me.

60
00:04:18,008 --> 00:04:20,594
Besides, you'd be surprised.

61
00:04:20,677 --> 00:04:24,181
Elizabethan England,
not so different from your time.

62
00:04:24,848 --> 00:04:28,018
Look over there. They've got recycling.

63
00:04:31,396 --> 00:04:33,273
A water cooler moment.

64
00:04:33,398 --> 00:04:36,443
...and the Earth
will be consumed by flame!

65
00:04:36,526 --> 00:04:40,197
Global warming.
Oh, yes, and entertainment.

66
00:04:40,322 --> 00:04:42,616
Popular entertainment for the masses.

67
00:04:42,699 --> 00:04:46,244
If I'm right, we're just down the river
by Southwark.

68
00:04:46,369 --> 00:04:48,371
Right next to...

69
00:04:50,207 --> 00:04:51,625
Oh, yes!

70
00:04:51,958 --> 00:04:54,377
The Globe Theatre!

71
00:04:54,461 --> 00:04:56,254
Brand-new, just opened.

72
00:04:56,338 --> 00:04:58,173
Though, strictly speaking,
it's not a globe.

73
00:04:58,256 --> 00:05:02,135
It's a tetradecagon, 14 sides,
containing the man himself.

74
00:05:02,761 --> 00:05:05,263
Whoa, you don't mean...

75
00:05:05,347 --> 00:05:07,974
-Is Shakespeare in there?
-Oh, yes.

76
00:05:08,058 --> 00:05:10,310
Miss Jones, will you accompany me
to the theatre?

77
00:05:10,393 --> 00:05:12,395
Mr Smith, I will!

78
00:05:12,521 --> 00:05:15,315
When you get home, you can tell everyone
you've seen Shakespeare.

79
00:05:15,398 --> 00:05:17,692
Then I could get sectioned.

80
00:05:18,735 --> 00:05:20,987
(AUDIENCE CHEERING)

81
00:05:39,923 --> 00:05:44,135
That's amazing, just amazing.
It's worth putting up with the smell.

82
00:05:46,263 --> 00:05:48,682
And those are men
dressed as women, yeah?

83
00:05:48,765 --> 00:05:50,934
London never changes.

84
00:05:51,810 --> 00:05:54,312
Where's Shakespeare?
I want to see Shakespeare!

85
00:05:54,396 --> 00:05:56,231
Author! Author!

86
00:05:56,690 --> 00:05:58,608
Do people shout that?
Do they shout "Author"?

87
00:05:58,733 --> 00:06:00,777
Author! Author!

88
00:06:00,861 --> 00:06:04,322
ALL: Author! Author!

89
00:06:04,447 --> 00:06:05,782
Well,

90
00:06:07,534 --> 00:06:09,452
they do now.

91
00:06:09,953 --> 00:06:12,080
-Author!
-Author!

92
00:06:22,257 --> 00:06:24,009
WOMAN: Author! Author!

93
00:06:24,134 --> 00:06:25,385
MAN: Author!

94
00:06:25,886 --> 00:06:27,554
Author!

95
00:06:29,347 --> 00:06:32,267
He's a bit different to his portraits.

96
00:06:52,495 --> 00:06:55,081
Genius. He's a genius, the genius.

97
00:06:55,165 --> 00:06:57,375
The most human human there's ever been.

98
00:06:57,459 --> 00:06:59,669
Now, we're gonna hear him speak.

99
00:06:59,753 --> 00:07:04,758
Always, he chooses the best words.
New, beautiful, brilliant words.

100
00:07:05,342 --> 00:07:08,345
Oh, shut your big, fat mouths!

101
00:07:12,307 --> 00:07:14,935
-Oh, well.
-You should never meet your heroes.

102
00:07:15,018 --> 00:07:18,021
You've got excellent taste,
I'll give you that.

103
00:07:18,146 --> 00:07:19,689
Oh, that's a wig.

104
00:07:19,814 --> 00:07:22,025
(ALL LAUGHING)

105
00:07:22,108 --> 00:07:24,694
Wind the craft of ancient harm.

106
00:07:25,278 --> 00:07:27,739
The time approaches for our charm.

107
00:07:27,822 --> 00:07:29,866
I know what you're all saying,

108
00:07:29,950 --> 00:07:32,786
“love's Labour's Lost
that's a funny ending, isn't it?"

109
00:07:32,869 --> 00:07:36,706
It just stops.
Will the boys get the girls?

110
00:07:36,790 --> 00:07:39,960
Well, don't get your hose in a tangle.
You'll find out soon.

111
00:07:40,043 --> 00:07:41,628
ALL: When?

112
00:07:41,711 --> 00:07:44,589
Yeah, yeah. All in good time.

113
00:07:44,673 --> 00:07:46,633
You don't rush a genius.

114
00:07:46,716 --> 00:07:48,134
(ALL LAUGHING)

115
00:07:52,138 --> 00:07:53,473
When?

116
00:07:55,433 --> 00:07:56,726
Tomorrow night.

117
00:07:56,810 --> 00:07:58,687
(ALL CHEERING)

118
00:08:00,063 --> 00:08:04,192
The premier of my brand-new play,
a sequel, no less.

119
00:08:04,275 --> 00:08:07,946
And I call it Love's Labour's Won.

120
00:08:08,071 --> 00:08:09,906
(ALL CHEERING)

121
00:08:16,121 --> 00:08:19,332
I'm not an expert, but I've never heard
of Love's Labour's Won.

122
00:08:19,416 --> 00:08:23,670
Exactly. The lost play.
Doesn't exist. I mean, rumours.

123
00:08:23,753 --> 00:08:26,715
It's mentioned in lists of his plays,
but never ever turns up,

124
00:08:26,798 --> 00:08:28,925
and no one knows why.

125
00:08:29,050 --> 00:08:31,177
Have you got a mini-disc or something?

126
00:08:31,302 --> 00:08:34,931
We can tape it, we can flog it.
Sell it when we get home, make a mint.

127
00:08:35,015 --> 00:08:36,474
No.

128
00:08:36,599 --> 00:08:39,269
-That would be bad.
-Yeah, yeah.

129
00:08:39,394 --> 00:08:41,771
How come it disappeared
in the first place?

130
00:08:41,896 --> 00:08:43,732
Well...

131
00:08:44,441 --> 00:08:48,361
Oh, I was just going to give you
a quick little trip in the Tardis,

132
00:08:48,445 --> 00:08:51,322
but I suppose
we could stay a bit longer.

133
00:09:05,837 --> 00:09:08,798
Here you go, Will, drink up.

134
00:09:08,882 --> 00:09:11,801
There's enough beer in
this lodgings house to sink the Spanish.

135
00:09:11,885 --> 00:09:13,970
Dolly Bailey, you've saved my life.

136
00:09:14,095 --> 00:09:16,848
I'll do more than that later tonight.

137
00:09:17,807 --> 00:09:19,726
And you, girl, hurry up with the tasks.

138
00:09:19,809 --> 00:09:21,895
The talk of gentlemen"s
best not overheard.

139
00:09:21,978 --> 00:09:23,438
Yeah, ma'am. Sorry, ma'am.

140
00:09:23,521 --> 00:09:26,816
You must be mad, Will.
Love's Labour's Won?We're not ready.

141
00:09:26,900 --> 00:09:29,027
It's supposed to be next week.
What made you say that?

142
00:09:29,152 --> 00:09:30,653
You haven't even finished it yet.

143
00:09:30,737 --> 00:09:32,947
I've just got the final scene to go.
You'll get it by morning.

144
00:09:33,031 --> 00:09:37,702
Hello! Excuse me. Not interrupting,
am I? Mr Shakespeare, isn't it?

145
00:09:37,827 --> 00:09:40,163
Oh, no, no, no. Who let you in?

146
00:09:40,246 --> 00:09:42,999
No autographs. No, you can't
have yourself sketched with me,

147
00:09:43,083 --> 00:09:45,376
and please don't ask
where I get my ideas from.

148
00:09:45,460 --> 00:09:49,047
Thanks for the interest.
Now be a good boy and shove...

149
00:09:50,465 --> 00:09:52,842
Hey, nonny, nonny!

150
00:09:52,967 --> 00:09:54,636
Sit right down here, next to me.

151
00:09:54,719 --> 00:09:57,764
You two get sewing on them costumes.
Off you go.

152
00:09:57,847 --> 00:10:01,392
Come on, lads. I think
our William's found his new muse.

153
00:10:01,518 --> 00:10:03,311
Sweet lady.

154
00:10:05,188 --> 00:10:07,398
Such unusual clothes.

155
00:10:07,482 --> 00:10:09,859
So fitted.

156
00:10:10,360 --> 00:10:13,446
Erm, verily, forsooth, egads!

157
00:10:13,530 --> 00:10:15,865
No, no, don't do that.

158
00:10:17,534 --> 00:10:21,663
I'm Sir Doctor of Tardis, and this is
my companion, Miss Martha Jones.

159
00:10:21,746 --> 00:10:24,791
Interesting.
That bit of paper, it's blank.

160
00:10:24,874 --> 00:10:26,501
Oh, that's...

161
00:10:27,127 --> 00:10:29,003
Very clever, that proves it.

162
00:10:29,087 --> 00:10:30,672
-Absolute genius.
-Hmm.

163
00:10:30,755 --> 00:10:33,633
No, it says right there, "Sir Doctor
and Martha Jones." It says so.

164
00:10:33,716 --> 00:10:35,468
I say it's blank.

165
00:10:35,552 --> 00:10:39,889
Psychic paper. Um... Long story.
Oh, I hate starting from scratch.

166
00:10:40,014 --> 00:10:42,559
Psychic? I've never heard that before,
and words are my trade.

167
00:10:42,642 --> 00:10:47,021
Who are you exactly? More to the point,
who is your delicious blackamoor lady?

168
00:10:47,105 --> 00:10:48,606
-What did you say?
-Whoops.

169
00:10:48,731 --> 00:10:51,192
Isn't that a word we use nowadays?

170
00:10:51,276 --> 00:10:54,612
An Ethiop girl, a swarth,
a Queen of Afric?

171
00:10:54,696 --> 00:10:57,615
-I can't believe I'm hearing this.
-It's political correctness gone mad.

172
00:10:57,740 --> 00:11:01,327
Martha's from a far off land, Freedonia.

173
00:11:01,411 --> 00:11:03,830
Excuse me. Hold hard a moment.

174
00:11:03,913 --> 00:11:06,332
This is abominable behaviour.

175
00:11:06,416 --> 00:11:08,459
A new play with no warning.

176
00:11:08,543 --> 00:11:11,045
I demand to see a script,
Mr Shakespeare.

177
00:11:11,129 --> 00:11:13,214
As Master of the Revels,

178
00:11:13,298 --> 00:11:16,009
every new script
must be registered at my office

179
00:11:16,092 --> 00:11:19,262
and examined by me
before it can be performed.

180
00:11:19,345 --> 00:11:21,222
Tomorrow morning, first thing,
I'll send it round.

181
00:11:21,306 --> 00:11:23,850
I don't work to your schedule,
you work to mine.

182
00:11:23,975 --> 00:11:26,519
-The script, now!
-I can't.

183
00:11:26,603 --> 00:11:29,022
Then tomorrow's performance
is cancelled.

184
00:11:29,105 --> 00:11:30,607
It's all go around here, isn't it?

185
00:11:30,690 --> 00:11:33,109
I'm returning to my office
for a banning order.

186
00:11:33,234 --> 00:11:35,278
If it's the last thing I do,

187
00:11:35,361 --> 00:11:38,323
Love's Labour's Won
will never be played.

188
00:11:41,868 --> 00:11:44,954
Ooh! Sorry, sir.
Begging your pardon, sir.

189
00:11:45,038 --> 00:11:47,582
Mind you don't hurt
that handsome head of yours.

190
00:11:47,665 --> 00:11:49,667
Hold hard, wanton woman!

191
00:11:50,877 --> 00:11:52,795
I shall return later.

192
00:12:02,847 --> 00:12:04,390
Oh, my mothers.

193
00:12:04,474 --> 00:12:08,102
There's one seeks to stop
the performance tomorrow.

194
00:12:08,186 --> 00:12:09,812
But it must be tomorrow!

195
00:12:09,896 --> 00:12:12,649
Love's Labour's Won must be performed.

196
00:12:12,732 --> 00:12:14,192
Fear not.

197
00:12:14,776 --> 00:12:16,611
Chant with me.

198
00:12:17,904 --> 00:12:20,615
Water damps the fiercest flame.

199
00:12:20,698 --> 00:12:23,660
Drowns down girls and boys the same.

200
00:12:35,338 --> 00:12:37,715
Well then, mystery solved.

201
00:12:37,840 --> 00:12:39,842
That's Love's Labour's Won
over and done with.

202
00:12:39,926 --> 00:12:43,721
I thought it might be something,
you know, more mysterious.

203
00:12:43,846 --> 00:12:45,640
(WOMAN SCREAMING)

204
00:12:47,517 --> 00:12:49,352
WOMAN: Help me!

205
00:13:02,615 --> 00:13:05,576
-It's that Lynley bloke.
-What's wrong with him?

206
00:13:05,702 --> 00:13:09,330
-Leave it to me, I'm a doctor.
-So am I. Near enough.

207
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:14,585
Now to halt the vital part.

208
00:13:14,711 --> 00:13:17,630
-Stab the flesh!
-Stop the heart.

209
00:13:21,551 --> 00:13:23,553
Eternal sleep is thine.

210
00:13:27,807 --> 00:13:32,562
Can't get the heart going. Mr Lynley!
Come on. Can you hear me?

211
00:13:33,646 --> 00:13:35,398
You're gonna be all right.

212
00:13:35,481 --> 00:13:36,858
(GURGLING)

213
00:13:36,941 --> 00:13:38,818
What the hell is that?

214
00:13:38,901 --> 00:13:43,573
I've never seen a death like it.
His lungs are full of water. He drowned.

215
00:13:44,157 --> 00:13:48,202
I don't know, like a blow to the heart.
A visible blow.

216
00:13:51,247 --> 00:13:54,917
Good mistress, this poor fellow has died
from a sudden imbalance of the humours.

217
00:13:55,001 --> 00:13:58,004
A natural, if unfortunate, demise.
Call the constable, have him taken away.

218
00:13:58,087 --> 00:14:00,423
-Yes, sir.
-I'll do it, ma'am.

219
00:14:04,010 --> 00:14:05,678
Why are you telling them that?

220
00:14:05,762 --> 00:14:07,680
This lot have still got
one foot in the Dark Ages.

221
00:14:07,764 --> 00:14:10,266
If I tell them the truth, they'll panic
and think it was witchcraft.

222
00:14:10,350 --> 00:14:12,769
Okay, what was it, then?

223
00:14:12,852 --> 00:14:14,479
Witchcraft.

224
00:14:15,271 --> 00:14:17,648
DOOMFINGER: The potion is prepared.

225
00:14:17,732 --> 00:14:19,817
Now, take it.

226
00:14:20,610 --> 00:14:24,655
Magic words
for the playwright's fevered mind.

227
00:14:24,781 --> 00:14:26,657
Shakespeare will release us.

228
00:14:26,741 --> 00:14:30,620
The mind of a genius
will unlock the tide of blood.

229
00:14:31,788 --> 00:14:34,665
Upon this night, the work is done.

230
00:14:34,957 --> 00:14:37,794
A muse to pen Love's Labour's Won.

231
00:14:50,765 --> 00:14:52,600
I got you a room, Sir Doctor.

232
00:14:52,683 --> 00:14:55,561
You and Miss Jones
are just across the landing.

233
00:14:55,645 --> 00:14:59,148
Poor Lynley. So many strange events.

234
00:14:59,232 --> 00:15:02,819
Not least of all, this land of Freedonia
where a woman can be a doctor.

235
00:15:02,944 --> 00:15:05,530
Where a woman can be what she likes.

236
00:15:05,655 --> 00:15:09,909
And you, Sir Doctor.
How can a man so young have eyes so old?

237
00:15:09,992 --> 00:15:12,036
I do a lot of reading.

238
00:15:12,161 --> 00:15:14,914
A trite reply, yeah? That's what I do.

239
00:15:16,541 --> 00:15:20,753
And you, you look at him
like you're surprised he exists.

240
00:15:20,837 --> 00:15:24,006
He's as much of a puzzle to you
as he is to me.

241
00:15:24,924 --> 00:15:27,677
I think we should say good night.

242
00:15:30,596 --> 00:15:34,016
I must to work.
I have a play to complete.

243
00:15:35,852 --> 00:15:39,439
I'll get my answers tomorrow, Doctor,
and I'll discover more about you

244
00:15:39,522 --> 00:15:42,984
and why this constant performance
of yours.

245
00:15:43,067 --> 00:15:45,361
All the world's a stage.

246
00:15:45,528 --> 00:15:47,864
Hmm. I might use that.

247
00:15:48,781 --> 00:15:50,700
Good night, Doctor.

248
00:15:50,783 --> 00:15:52,910
Nighty-night, Shakespeare.

249
00:16:01,669 --> 00:16:03,963
It's not exactly five star, is it?

250
00:16:04,046 --> 00:16:06,090
Oh, it'll do. I've seen worse.

251
00:16:06,174 --> 00:16:09,260
-I haven't even got a toothbrush.
-Ooh, um...

252
00:16:10,970 --> 00:16:13,055
Contains Venusian spearmint.

253
00:16:13,222 --> 00:16:16,392
So, who's going where?
I mean, there's only one bed.

254
00:16:16,476 --> 00:16:18,644
We'll manage. Come on.

255
00:16:21,814 --> 00:16:24,984
So, magic and stuff. That's a surprise.

256
00:16:25,067 --> 00:16:27,195
It's all a bit Harry Potter.

257
00:16:27,278 --> 00:16:31,282
Wait till you read book seven.
Oh, I cried!

258
00:16:31,365 --> 00:16:34,785
But is it real, though? I mean, witches,
black magic and all that, it's real?

259
00:16:34,869 --> 00:16:37,580
-Course it isn't!
-Well, how am I supposed to know?

260
00:16:37,663 --> 00:16:40,291
I've only just started believing in
time travel. Give me a break.

261
00:16:40,374 --> 00:16:42,919
Looks like witchcraft, but it isn't.

262
00:16:43,002 --> 00:16:46,339
It can't be.
Are you gonna stand there all night?

263
00:16:51,886 --> 00:16:53,971
Budge up a bit, then.

264
00:16:54,597 --> 00:16:56,933
Sorry, there's not much room.

265
00:16:57,016 --> 00:17:00,436
Us two here, same bed. Tongues will wag.

266
00:17:00,520 --> 00:17:02,313
There's such a thing as psychic energy,

267
00:17:02,396 --> 00:17:04,690
but a human
couldn't channel it like that.

268
00:17:04,774 --> 00:17:06,692
Not without a generator
the size of Taunton,

269
00:17:06,776 --> 00:17:09,654
and I think we'd have spotted that. No.

270
00:17:12,031 --> 00:17:14,784
There's something I'm missing, Martha.

271
00:17:15,910 --> 00:17:17,954
Something really close.

272
00:17:18,871 --> 00:17:22,500
It's staring me right in the face,
and I can't see it.

273
00:17:25,127 --> 00:17:27,296
Rose would know.

274
00:17:29,173 --> 00:17:33,553
A friend of mine, Rose, right now
she'd say exactly the right thing.

275
00:17:36,138 --> 00:17:39,642
Still, can't be helped.
You're a novice, never mind.

276
00:17:40,560 --> 00:17:42,728
I'll take you back home tomorrow.

277
00:17:42,812 --> 00:17:44,230
Great!

278
00:18:36,949 --> 00:18:40,536
Bind the mind and take the man.

279
00:18:41,370 --> 00:18:43,623
Speed the words

280
00:18:44,415 --> 00:18:46,459
to writer's hand.

281
00:19:29,877 --> 00:19:34,340
Will, I finished cleaning,
just in time for your special treat.

282
00:19:34,423 --> 00:19:36,967
Oh, aye. I'm not the first, then.

283
00:19:39,261 --> 00:19:44,183
I'll take that to aid my flight
and you shall speak no more this night.

284
00:19:44,266 --> 00:19:46,352
(SCREAMING)

285
00:19:51,774 --> 00:19:53,109
What?

286
00:19:54,860 --> 00:19:57,029
SHAKESPEARE: What was that?

287
00:19:57,822 --> 00:19:59,782
(CACKLING)

288
00:20:00,074 --> 00:20:01,951
Her heart gave out.

289
00:20:02,368 --> 00:20:03,953
She died of fright.

290
00:20:04,036 --> 00:20:05,454
Doctor?

291
00:20:06,038 --> 00:20:07,498
What did you see?

292
00:20:07,581 --> 00:20:09,083
A witch.

293
00:20:15,464 --> 00:20:18,050
SHAKESPEARE: Oh, sweet Dolly Bailey.

294
00:20:18,134 --> 00:20:22,638
She sat out three bouts of the plague
in this place. We all ran like rats.

295
00:20:22,722 --> 00:20:26,142
But what could have scared her so?
She had such enormous spirit.

296
00:20:26,225 --> 00:20:29,311
Rage, rage,
against the dying of the light.

297
00:20:29,854 --> 00:20:31,272
I might use that.

298
00:20:31,355 --> 00:20:33,107
You can't, it's someone else's.

299
00:20:33,190 --> 00:20:37,319
But the thing is, Lynley drowned
on dry land, Dolly died of fright

300
00:20:37,403 --> 00:20:40,281
-and they were both connected to you.
-You're accusing me?

301
00:20:40,364 --> 00:20:44,660
No, but I saw a witch, big as you like,
flying, cackling away,

302
00:20:44,744 --> 00:20:47,371
-and you've written about witches.
-I have? When was that?

303
00:20:47,455 --> 00:20:49,290
Not... Not quite yet.

304
00:20:49,373 --> 00:20:51,792
-Peter Streete spoke of witches.
-Who's Peter Streete?

305
00:20:51,876 --> 00:20:53,919
Our builder.
He sketched the plans for the Globe.

306
00:20:54,003 --> 00:20:55,588
The architect?

307
00:20:56,338 --> 00:20:59,633
Hold on. The architect. The architect!
The Globe! Come on!

308
00:21:01,427 --> 00:21:04,430
Columns there, right, and 14 sides.

309
00:21:04,972 --> 00:21:06,766
I've always wondered,
but I've never asked.

310
00:21:06,849 --> 00:21:08,350
Tell me, Will, why 14 sides?

311
00:21:08,434 --> 00:21:11,061
It was the shape Peter Streete
thought best, that's all.

312
00:21:11,145 --> 00:21:14,273
-He said it carried the sound well.
-147?

313
00:21:14,690 --> 00:21:16,567
Why does that ring a bell? 14?

314
00:21:16,650 --> 00:21:20,070
-There's 14 lines in a sonnet.
-So there is.

315
00:21:20,154 --> 00:21:23,491
Good point. Words and shapes
following the same design.

316
00:21:23,574 --> 00:21:25,618
14 lines, 14 sides, 14 facets...
My head!

317
00:21:25,701 --> 00:21:27,661
Tetradecagon, think, think, think!

318
00:21:27,745 --> 00:21:30,414
-Words, letters, numbers, lines!
-This is just a theatre!

319
00:21:30,498 --> 00:21:33,083
Oh, yeah,
but a theatre's magic, isn't it?

320
00:21:33,167 --> 00:21:35,795
You should know.
You stand on this stage,

321
00:21:35,878 --> 00:21:38,964
say the right words with
the right emphasis at the right time.

322
00:21:39,048 --> 00:21:41,425
Oh, you can make men weep

323
00:21:41,550 --> 00:21:43,594
or cry with joy.

324
00:21:43,677 --> 00:21:45,763
Change them.

325
00:21:46,514 --> 00:21:50,518
You can change peoples" minds
just with words in this place.

326
00:21:52,895 --> 00:21:54,647
And if you exaggerate that...

327
00:21:54,730 --> 00:21:58,275
It's like your police box. Small,
wooden box with all that power inside.

328
00:21:58,359 --> 00:22:03,489
Oh! Oh, Martha Jones, I like you.
Tell you what, Peter Streete would know.

329
00:22:03,572 --> 00:22:06,033
-Can I talk to him?
-You won't get an answer.

330
00:22:06,116 --> 00:22:08,536
A month after finishing this place,
he lost his mind.

331
00:22:08,619 --> 00:22:09,995
Why, what happened?

332
00:22:10,079 --> 00:22:12,957
He started raving about witches,
hearing voices, babbling.

333
00:22:13,040 --> 00:22:14,583
-His mind was addled.
-Where is he now?

334
00:22:14,667 --> 00:22:16,210
-Bedlam.
-What's Bedlam?

335
00:22:16,293 --> 00:22:19,630
-Bethlem Hospital, the madhouse.
-We gotta go there, right now. Come on!

336
00:22:19,755 --> 00:22:23,259
Wait, I'm coming with you.
I want to witness this at first hand.

337
00:22:23,342 --> 00:22:25,636
Ralph! The last scene, as promised.

338
00:22:25,761 --> 00:22:27,555
Copy it, hand it around,
learn it, speak it.

339
00:22:27,638 --> 00:22:30,182
Back before curtain up,
and remember, kid, project!

340
00:22:30,266 --> 00:22:34,228
Eyes and teeth.
You never know, the Queen might turn up.

341
00:22:34,311 --> 00:22:36,272
As if. She never does.

342
00:22:38,148 --> 00:22:42,444
So, tell me of Freedonia, where women
can be doctors, writers, actors.

343
00:22:42,570 --> 00:22:43,863
This country's ruled by a woman.

344
00:22:43,946 --> 00:22:47,867
Ah, she's royal, that's God's business.
Though you are a royal beauty.

345
00:22:47,950 --> 00:22:51,829
Whoa, Nelly! I know for a fact
you've got a wife in the country.

346
00:22:51,954 --> 00:22:53,247
But, Martha, this is town.

347
00:22:53,330 --> 00:22:55,457
Come on,
we can all have a good flirt later!

348
00:22:55,583 --> 00:22:57,960
Is that a promise, Doctor?

349
00:22:58,085 --> 00:23:02,256
Oh, 57 academics just punched the air.
Now, move!

350
00:23:05,634 --> 00:23:07,428
Love's Labour's Won.

351
00:23:07,511 --> 00:23:09,889
I don't think much of sequels,
they're never as good as the original.

352
00:23:09,972 --> 00:23:11,348
Have you seen this last bit?

353
00:23:11,473 --> 00:23:14,310
Must have been dozing off when he wrote
that. I don't even know what it means.

354
00:23:14,435 --> 00:23:18,230
Well, that goes for most of his stuff.
Ah, but at least it's my speech.

355
00:23:18,314 --> 00:23:19,440
(LAUGHS)

356
00:23:19,523 --> 00:23:21,400
I get centre stage.

357
00:23:22,860 --> 00:23:25,613
"The light of Shadmoch's hollow moon

358
00:23:25,738 --> 00:23:27,990
"doth shine on to a point in space,

359
00:23:28,073 --> 00:23:30,284
"betwixt Dravidian shore..."

360
00:23:30,367 --> 00:23:32,703
(WIND GUSTING)

361
00:23:33,954 --> 00:23:35,915
What was that?

362
00:23:35,998 --> 00:23:41,337
"...Dravidian shores,
linear 5-9-3-0-1-6..."

363
00:23:42,171 --> 00:23:44,840
A spirit stirs the ether.

364
00:23:45,674 --> 00:23:48,218
But too soon, too soon!

365
00:23:49,261 --> 00:23:51,347
Not to fear, my mothers.

366
00:23:52,014 --> 00:23:54,975
'Tis merely a rehearsal
of what's to come.

367
00:23:57,144 --> 00:24:01,023
"...and strikes the fulsome grove
of Rexel 4."

368
00:24:03,692 --> 00:24:05,444
By all the saints.

369
00:24:06,695 --> 00:24:08,405
It's a spirit.

370
00:24:08,530 --> 00:24:09,907
(SQUAWKING)

371
00:24:10,032 --> 00:24:12,034
It's a vile shade.

372
00:24:13,535 --> 00:24:15,579
(SHRIEKING)

373
00:24:18,832 --> 00:24:21,961
I think we should never
speak of this again.

374
00:24:22,044 --> 00:24:24,797
Else we'll end up in Bedlam ourselves.

375
00:24:25,881 --> 00:24:29,134
(PATIENTS WAILING)

376
00:24:31,095 --> 00:24:32,513
Please, please!

377
00:24:32,596 --> 00:24:36,100
Does my lord Doctor wish
some entertainment while he waits?

378
00:24:36,225 --> 00:24:39,311
I can whip these madmen.
They'll put on a good show for you.

379
00:24:39,395 --> 00:24:42,314
-Bandog and Bedlam.
-No, I don't.

380
00:24:42,398 --> 00:24:45,234
Well, wait here, my lords,
while I, uh...

381
00:24:45,317 --> 00:24:47,736
Make him decent for the lady.

382
00:24:47,820 --> 00:24:49,655
So this is what you call
a hospital, yeah?

383
00:24:49,738 --> 00:24:52,199
Where the patients are whipped
to entertain the gentry?

384
00:24:52,282 --> 00:24:56,286
-And you put your friend in here?
-Oh, it's all so different in Freedonia.

385
00:24:56,412 --> 00:24:59,498
But you're clever! Do you honestly think
this place is any good?

386
00:24:59,581 --> 00:25:01,375
I've been mad, I've lost my mind.

387
00:25:01,458 --> 00:25:04,336
Fear of this place set me right again.
Serves its purpose.

388
00:25:04,420 --> 00:25:07,339
-Mad in what way?
-You lost your son.

389
00:25:07,423 --> 00:25:09,883
My only boy. The Black Death took him.

390
00:25:10,009 --> 00:25:11,760
I wasn't even there.

391
00:25:11,885 --> 00:25:14,304
-I didn't know, I'm sorry.
-Made me question everything.

392
00:25:14,430 --> 00:25:18,434
The futility of this fleeting existence,
to be or not to be.

393
00:25:19,018 --> 00:25:21,437
Oh, that's quite good.

394
00:25:21,937 --> 00:25:26,358
-You should write that down.
-Hmm, maybe not. A bit pretentious?

395
00:25:26,442 --> 00:25:28,360
This way, my lord.

396
00:25:30,779 --> 00:25:33,032
(PATIENTS WAILING)

397
00:25:44,543 --> 00:25:46,962
They can be dangerous, my lord.
Don't know their own strength.

398
00:25:47,046 --> 00:25:50,716
I think it helps if you don't whip them.
Now, get out!

399
00:25:54,595 --> 00:25:55,846
Peter.

400
00:25:57,264 --> 00:25:59,266
Peter Streete.

401
00:25:59,349 --> 00:26:03,145
He's the same as he was.
You'll get nothing out of him.

402
00:26:05,606 --> 00:26:06,815
Peter.

403
00:26:12,488 --> 00:26:14,031
What is this?

404
00:26:14,740 --> 00:26:16,408
I must see!

405
00:26:22,539 --> 00:26:24,249
That stranger...

406
00:26:25,000 --> 00:26:27,544
He was at the inn with Shakespeare.

407
00:26:27,628 --> 00:26:30,047
I thought then
he smelt of something new.

408
00:26:30,130 --> 00:26:32,466
Now he visits the madhouse.

409
00:26:32,549 --> 00:26:34,468
The architect!

410
00:26:42,518 --> 00:26:44,520
Peter, I'm the Doctor.

411
00:26:46,230 --> 00:26:48,023
Go into the past.

412
00:26:48,982 --> 00:26:50,609
One year ago.

413
00:26:50,692 --> 00:26:52,694
Let your mind go back.

414
00:26:53,695 --> 00:26:56,740
Back to when everything
was fine and shiny.

415
00:26:58,158 --> 00:27:02,621
Everything that happened in this year
since happened to somebody else.

416
00:27:02,704 --> 00:27:04,498
It's just a story.

417
00:27:05,374 --> 00:27:07,167
A winter's tale.

418
00:27:08,544 --> 00:27:10,212
Let go.

419
00:27:10,337 --> 00:27:12,422
That's it. That's it.

420
00:27:13,382 --> 00:27:14,967
Just let go.

421
00:27:17,886 --> 00:27:19,429
(GASPING)

422
00:27:19,555 --> 00:27:21,682
Tell me the story, Peter.

423
00:27:22,641 --> 00:27:24,810
Tell me about the witches.

424
00:27:24,893 --> 00:27:28,939
Who is this Doctor? Why does he come now
at our time of glory?

425
00:27:30,190 --> 00:27:32,609
Doomfinger, transport yourself.

426
00:27:33,402 --> 00:27:35,154
Doom the Doctor.

427
00:27:35,404 --> 00:27:37,197
Doom his hide.

428
00:27:41,034 --> 00:27:43,328
Witches spoke to Peter.

429
00:27:44,955 --> 00:27:48,250
In the night,
they whispered, they whispered...

430
00:27:53,130 --> 00:27:57,050
Got Peter to build the Globe
to their design, their design!

431
00:27:58,177 --> 00:27:59,761
The 14 walls.

432
00:28:00,554 --> 00:28:02,181
Always 14.

433
00:28:03,682 --> 00:28:05,017
When the work was done...

434
00:28:05,142 --> 00:28:07,227
(LAUGHING MANIACALLY)

435
00:28:08,270 --> 00:28:11,857
They snapped poor Peter's wits.

436
00:28:11,940 --> 00:28:15,736
Well, where did Peter see the witches?
Where in the city?

437
00:28:16,528 --> 00:28:18,155
Peter, tell me!

438
00:28:18,238 --> 00:28:21,074
You've got to tell me. Where were they?

439
00:28:23,410 --> 00:28:24,953
All Hallows Street.

440
00:28:25,078 --> 00:28:26,705
Too many words!

441
00:28:26,788 --> 00:28:29,875
-What the hell?
-Just one touch

442
00:28:29,958 --> 00:28:31,793
of the heart.

443
00:28:32,419 --> 00:28:33,545
No!

444
00:28:38,050 --> 00:28:40,177
A witch! I'm seeing a witch!

445
00:28:40,260 --> 00:28:42,679
Now, who would be next, hmm?

446
00:28:42,763 --> 00:28:45,641
Just one touch.

447
00:28:48,644 --> 00:28:52,564
Oh, I'll stop your frantic hearts.

448
00:28:52,648 --> 00:28:55,067
Poor, fragile mortals.

449
00:28:55,150 --> 00:28:56,985
Let us out! Let us out!

450
00:28:57,110 --> 00:28:59,279
That's not going to work.
The whole building's shouting that.

451
00:28:59,363 --> 00:29:02,324
And who would die first, hmm?

452
00:29:02,407 --> 00:29:04,618
Well, if you're looking
for volunteers...

453
00:29:04,701 --> 00:29:06,870
-No, don't!
-Doctor, can you stop her?

454
00:29:06,995 --> 00:29:09,122
No mortal has power over me!

455
00:29:09,206 --> 00:29:11,541
No, but there's a power in words.

456
00:29:11,667 --> 00:29:13,919
If I can find the right one,
if I can just know you...

457
00:29:14,002 --> 00:29:16,255
None on Earth has knowledge of us.

458
00:29:16,338 --> 00:29:18,674
Well, it's a good thing I'm here.
Now, think, think, think.

459
00:29:18,799 --> 00:29:21,343
Humanoid, female, who uses
shapes and words to channel energy...

460
00:29:21,468 --> 00:29:23,262
Ah, 14!

461
00:29:23,387 --> 00:29:25,097
That's it, 14!

462
00:29:25,180 --> 00:29:28,600
The 14 stars of
the Rexel planetary configuration!

463
00:29:28,684 --> 00:29:30,894
Creature, I name you

464
00:29:30,978 --> 00:29:32,312
Carrionite!

465
00:29:32,396 --> 00:29:34,564
(SHRIEKING)

466
00:29:39,194 --> 00:29:41,280
-What did you do?
-I named her.

467
00:29:41,363 --> 00:29:44,783
The power of a name. That's old magic.

468
00:29:44,866 --> 00:29:46,451
But there's no such thing as magic.

469
00:29:46,535 --> 00:29:49,246
Well, it's just a different sort of
science. You lot, you chose mathematics.

470
00:29:49,371 --> 00:29:52,291
Given the right string of numbers, the
right equation, you can split the atom.

471
00:29:52,374 --> 00:29:54,376
The Carrionites use words instead.

472
00:29:54,459 --> 00:29:56,295
Use them for what?

473
00:29:57,129 --> 00:29:59,047
The end of the world.

474
00:30:00,549 --> 00:30:03,343
(WHEEZING)

475
00:30:06,054 --> 00:30:08,307
He knows us!

476
00:30:08,390 --> 00:30:10,267
He spoke our name!

477
00:30:11,727 --> 00:30:15,063
Then he will know death.
He will perish at my hand.

478
00:30:15,188 --> 00:30:16,481
(BELL CHIMING)

479
00:30:16,565 --> 00:30:19,067
My mothers, the time approaches.

480
00:30:19,192 --> 00:30:22,612
You must away to the Globe.
Go, I will join you.

481
00:30:22,738 --> 00:30:25,782
As soon as this Doctor screams his last.

482
00:30:27,075 --> 00:30:30,203
The Carrionites disappeared
way back at the dawn of the universe.

483
00:30:30,287 --> 00:30:32,164
Nobody was sure
if they were real or legend.

484
00:30:32,247 --> 00:30:34,666
-Well, I'm going for real.
-But what do they want?

485
00:30:34,750 --> 00:30:37,044
A new empire on Earth.

486
00:30:38,462 --> 00:30:41,548
A world of bones and blood
and witchcraft.

487
00:30:41,631 --> 00:30:43,342
But how?

488
00:30:43,425 --> 00:30:46,511
I'm looking at the man with the words.

489
00:30:46,595 --> 00:30:49,014
Me? But I've done nothing.

490
00:30:49,097 --> 00:30:51,016
Hold on, though.
What were you doing last night

491
00:30:51,099 --> 00:30:52,601
when that Carrionite was in the room?

492
00:30:52,726 --> 00:30:55,103
Finishing the play.

493
00:30:55,187 --> 00:30:57,564
What happens on the last page?

494
00:30:57,647 --> 00:31:00,108
The boys get the girls,
they have a bit of a dance.

495
00:31:00,192 --> 00:31:03,320
It's all as funny and
thought-provoking as usual.

496
00:31:03,445 --> 00:31:06,281
Except those last few lines.

497
00:31:06,406 --> 00:31:10,202
Funny thing is,
I don't actually remember writing them.

498
00:31:10,285 --> 00:31:11,745
That's it!

499
00:31:12,579 --> 00:31:16,249
They used you.
They gave you the final words.

500
00:31:16,333 --> 00:31:19,378
Like a spell, like a code.
Love's Labour's Won, it's a weapon!

501
00:31:19,461 --> 00:31:21,380
The right combination of words
spoken in the right place

502
00:31:21,505 --> 00:31:23,882
with the shape of the Globe
as an energy converter!

503
00:31:23,965 --> 00:31:25,801
The play is the thing!

504
00:31:25,884 --> 00:31:28,136
And yes, you can have that.

505
00:31:36,812 --> 00:31:40,899
We left the lovers of Navarre,
by cruel chance separated,

506
00:31:41,024 --> 00:31:44,027
none to claim his heart,
their lab ours lost.

507
00:31:44,152 --> 00:31:47,280
Now will they find love's labour's won?

508
00:31:55,163 --> 00:31:57,833
All Hallows Street, there it is.
Martha, we'll track them down.

509
00:31:57,916 --> 00:32:00,752
Will, you get to the Globe.
Whatever you do, stop that play!

510
00:32:00,836 --> 00:32:03,588
I'll do it. All these years,
I've been the cleverest man around.

511
00:32:03,672 --> 00:32:05,173
Next to you, I know nothing.

512
00:32:05,257 --> 00:32:08,176
-Well, don't complain.
-I'm not! It's marvellous.

513
00:32:08,260 --> 00:32:10,053
-Good luck, Doctor.
-Good luck, Shakespeare.

514
00:32:10,178 --> 00:32:13,098
-Once more unto the breach!
-I like that!

515
00:32:13,181 --> 00:32:15,100
Wait a minute, that's one of mine.

516
00:32:15,225 --> 00:32:17,185
Oh, just shift!

517
00:32:17,853 --> 00:32:21,189
The eye should have contentment
where it rests...

518
00:32:23,650 --> 00:32:27,154
Patience, my sisters. Patience.

519
00:32:27,237 --> 00:32:30,824
-...mewling poor, drooped men...
-Stop the play!

520
00:32:30,907 --> 00:32:34,119
I'm sorry,
ladies and gentlemen, but stop.

521
00:32:34,202 --> 00:32:36,705
This performance must end immediately.

522
00:32:36,830 --> 00:32:38,206
Oh, everyone's a critic.

523
00:32:38,290 --> 00:32:40,375
-The wordsmith!
-Fear not.

524
00:32:40,459 --> 00:32:42,586
I have the doll.

525
00:32:42,711 --> 00:32:44,880
I'm sorry. You'll get a refund.

526
00:32:45,005 --> 00:32:47,841
But this play must not be performed.

527
00:32:51,386 --> 00:32:54,723
-Is he drunk, or what?
-Get him out of the way!

528
00:32:59,060 --> 00:33:02,105
You must forgive our irksome Will.

529
00:33:02,230 --> 00:33:03,857
He's been on the beer,

530
00:33:03,940 --> 00:33:06,276
and feeling ill.

531
00:33:11,406 --> 00:33:13,867
There is naught can stop us now.

532
00:33:16,578 --> 00:33:18,538
All Hallows Street.

533
00:33:19,080 --> 00:33:20,999
Which house?

534
00:33:21,082 --> 00:33:23,418
Thing is, though,
am I missing something here?

535
00:33:23,502 --> 00:33:27,631
The world didn't end in 1599, it just
didn't. Look at me, I'm living proof.

536
00:33:27,756 --> 00:33:30,675
Oh, how to explain the mechanics
of the infinite temporal flux?

537
00:33:30,759 --> 00:33:34,304
I know, Back to the Future!
It's like Back to the Future.

538
00:33:34,387 --> 00:33:37,557
-The film?
-No, the novelisation. Yes, the film!

539
00:33:37,641 --> 00:33:39,643
Marty McFly goes back
and changes history.

540
00:33:39,768 --> 00:33:43,355
And he starts fading away...
Oh, my God, am I going to fade?

541
00:33:43,438 --> 00:33:46,024
You and the entire future
of the human race.

542
00:33:46,107 --> 00:33:49,402
It ends right now, in 1599,
if we don't stop it.

543
00:33:50,153 --> 00:33:51,947
But which house?

544
00:33:52,948 --> 00:33:54,783
(CREAKING)

545
00:33:58,787 --> 00:34:01,039
Make that witch house.

546
00:34:12,801 --> 00:34:14,636
I take it we're expected?

547
00:34:14,719 --> 00:34:18,598
Oh, I think death has been
waiting for you a very long time.

548
00:34:18,682 --> 00:34:20,976
Right then, it's my turn.

549
00:34:21,059 --> 00:34:23,186
I know how to do this.

550
00:34:23,270 --> 00:34:25,105
I name thee

551
00:34:25,188 --> 00:34:26,398
Carrionite!

552
00:34:26,481 --> 00:34:27,816
(GASPS)

553
00:34:28,441 --> 00:34:30,235
What did I do wrong? Was it the finger?

554
00:34:30,318 --> 00:34:33,822
Power of a name
works only once. Observe.

555
00:34:33,905 --> 00:34:35,991
I gaze upon this bag of bones,

556
00:34:36,074 --> 00:34:38,660
and now I name thee, Martha Jones.

557
00:34:39,119 --> 00:34:41,705
What have you done?

558
00:34:41,830 --> 00:34:43,748
Only sleeping, alas.

559
00:34:43,832 --> 00:34:47,002
It's curious, her name has less impact.

560
00:34:47,085 --> 00:34:49,838
She's somehow out of her time.

561
00:34:49,921 --> 00:34:52,340
And as for you, Sir Doctor.

562
00:34:53,925 --> 00:34:55,385
Fascinating.

563
00:34:56,428 --> 00:34:58,179
There is no name.

564
00:34:58,263 --> 00:35:01,516
Why would a man hide his title
in such despair?

565
00:35:03,602 --> 00:35:05,520
Oh, but look.

566
00:35:06,354 --> 00:35:08,898
There's still one word
with a power that aches.

567
00:35:08,982 --> 00:35:12,694
-The naming won't work on me.
-But your heart grows cold.

568
00:35:12,819 --> 00:35:16,698
The north wind blows
and carries down the distant...

569
00:35:17,532 --> 00:35:18,992
Rose.

570
00:35:19,743 --> 00:35:24,289
Oh, big mistake.
'Cause that name keeps me fighting.

571
00:35:24,372 --> 00:35:26,958
The Carrionites vanished.
Where did you go?

572
00:35:27,042 --> 00:35:30,754
The Eternals found the right word
to banish us into deep darkness.

573
00:35:30,837 --> 00:35:33,298
-Then how did you escape?
-New words.

574
00:35:33,381 --> 00:35:35,467
New and glittering.

575
00:35:35,592 --> 00:35:37,385
From a mind like no other.

576
00:35:37,469 --> 00:35:39,012
Shakespeare.

577
00:35:41,014 --> 00:35:42,724
His son perished.

578
00:35:43,558 --> 00:35:46,019
The grief of a genius.

579
00:35:46,102 --> 00:35:48,355
Grief without measure.

580
00:35:48,438 --> 00:35:50,857
Madness enough to allow us entrance.

581
00:35:50,940 --> 00:35:53,818
-How many of you?
-Just the three.

582
00:35:53,902 --> 00:35:56,237
But the play tonight
shall restore the rest.

583
00:35:56,321 --> 00:35:59,908
Then the human race
will be purged as pestilence.

584
00:36:00,575 --> 00:36:03,495
And from this world
we will lead the universe back

585
00:36:03,578 --> 00:36:06,247
into the old ways of blood and magic.

586
00:36:06,915 --> 00:36:08,708
Mmm, busy schedule.

587
00:36:08,792 --> 00:36:10,919
But first,

588
00:36:11,002 --> 00:36:13,254
you've got to get past me.

589
00:36:13,755 --> 00:36:16,132
Oh, that should be a pleasure.

590
00:36:16,257 --> 00:36:21,137
Considering my enemy
has such a handsome shape.

591
00:36:21,262 --> 00:36:25,350
Now, that's one form of magic
that's definitely not gonna work on me.

592
00:36:25,433 --> 00:36:26,559
Oh, we'll see.

593
00:36:26,643 --> 00:36:28,269
(SCISSORS SNIPPING)

594
00:36:28,353 --> 00:36:31,439
-What was that for? What did you do?
-Souvenir.

595
00:36:31,564 --> 00:36:33,358
Well, give it back!

596
00:36:37,153 --> 00:36:39,030
Well, that's just cheating.

597
00:36:39,155 --> 00:36:45,120
Behold, Doctor. Men to Carrionites
are nothing but puppets.

598
00:36:46,413 --> 00:36:51,126
Now, you might call that magic,
I'd call that a DNA replication module.

599
00:36:51,209 --> 00:36:53,753
What use is your science now?

600
00:36:59,801 --> 00:37:01,720
Oh, my God, Doctor!

601
00:37:01,803 --> 00:37:04,013
Don't worry, I've got you.

602
00:37:07,475 --> 00:37:10,812
Hold on, mister. Two hearts?

603
00:37:10,895 --> 00:37:13,231
I'm making a habit of it.

604
00:37:15,525 --> 00:37:18,403
I've only got one heart working!

605
00:37:18,695 --> 00:37:20,822
How do you people cope?

606
00:37:20,905 --> 00:37:24,492
I've got to get the other one started.
Hit me! Hit me on the chest!

607
00:37:25,326 --> 00:37:26,828
Other side!

608
00:37:27,662 --> 00:37:29,831
Now, on the back, on the back!

609
00:37:29,914 --> 00:37:31,833
(GRUNTING) Left a bit!

610
00:37:33,460 --> 00:37:36,212
Lovely. There we go. By-da-boom-ba!

611
00:37:36,838 --> 00:37:40,675
Well, what are you standing there for?
Come on, the Globe!

612
00:37:43,052 --> 00:37:45,555
-The Doctor?
-Dead.

613
00:37:45,680 --> 00:37:47,432
The ladies have prepared a show.

614
00:37:47,557 --> 00:37:52,020
Maria means to present Isis
to send him from the dewy orb of heaven.

615
00:37:52,145 --> 00:37:54,147
Ah! Here comes Costard.

616
00:37:54,230 --> 00:37:55,815
(ALL CHEERING)

617
00:37:58,526 --> 00:37:59,903
Masters.

618
00:38:02,864 --> 00:38:05,825
-We're going the wrong way!
-No, we're not!

619
00:38:06,868 --> 00:38:09,370
DOCTOR: We're going the wrong way!

620
00:38:11,664 --> 00:38:14,167
Behold the swinish sight
of woman's love.

621
00:38:14,250 --> 00:38:17,170
Pish! It's out of season
to be heavy disposed.

622
00:38:17,253 --> 00:38:19,005
It is now, my mothers.

623
00:38:19,088 --> 00:38:21,966
The final words
to activate the tetradecagon.

624
00:38:22,050 --> 00:38:24,260
Betwixt Dravidian shores

625
00:38:24,344 --> 00:38:29,307
and linear 5-9-3-0-1-6-7 point 0-2,

626
00:38:29,390 --> 00:38:32,644
and strikes the fulsome grove
of Rexel 4.

627
00:38:32,727 --> 00:38:35,230
Co-radiating crystal, activate!

628
00:38:35,730 --> 00:38:37,774
The portal opens!

629
00:38:37,899 --> 00:38:39,359
It begins!

630
00:38:44,072 --> 00:38:47,325
I told thee so! I told thee!

631
00:38:50,411 --> 00:38:51,830
Stage door!

632
00:38:58,044 --> 00:39:00,588
(AUDIENCE SHRIEKING IN PANIC)

633
00:39:02,507 --> 00:39:04,425
(LAUGHING WICKEDLY)

634
00:39:11,516 --> 00:39:14,769
Stop the play! I think that was it.
Yeah, I said stop the play!

635
00:39:14,853 --> 00:39:17,856
-I hit my head.
-Yeah, don't rub it, you'll go bald.

636
00:39:17,981 --> 00:39:19,941
I think that's my cue.

637
00:39:21,359 --> 00:39:25,613
Now begins the millennium of blood!

638
00:39:30,368 --> 00:39:33,079
The Doctor! He lives.

639
00:39:33,162 --> 00:39:36,332
Then watch this world
become a blasted heath.

640
00:39:36,457 --> 00:39:38,585
They come, they come!

641
00:40:12,744 --> 00:40:15,622
-Come on, Will, history needs you.
-But what can I do?

642
00:40:15,705 --> 00:40:18,166
-Reverse it!
-How am I supposed to do that?

643
00:40:18,291 --> 00:40:21,169
The shape of the Globe gives
words power, but you're the wordsmith.

644
00:40:21,252 --> 00:40:23,713
The one true genius,
the only man clever enough to do it.

645
00:40:23,838 --> 00:40:25,757
But what words? I have none ready.

646
00:40:25,840 --> 00:40:27,508
You're William Shakespeare!

647
00:40:27,634 --> 00:40:31,220
But these Carrionite phrases,
they need such precision.

648
00:40:31,346 --> 00:40:33,932
Trust yourself.
When you're locked away in your room,

649
00:40:34,015 --> 00:40:35,600
the words just come, don't they?
Like magic.

650
00:40:35,683 --> 00:40:37,894
Words of the right sound,
the right shape, the right rhythm,

651
00:40:37,977 --> 00:40:39,687
words that last forever!

652
00:40:39,812 --> 00:40:42,857
That's what you do, Will.
You choose perfect words.

653
00:40:42,982 --> 00:40:45,026
Do it! Improvise!

654
00:40:51,991 --> 00:40:55,119
Close up this din
of hateful, dire decay,

655
00:40:55,203 --> 00:40:57,747
decomposition of your witches' plot!

656
00:40:57,872 --> 00:41:00,541
You thieve my brains,
consider me your toy,

657
00:41:00,625 --> 00:41:03,211
my doting Doctor tells me I am not!

658
00:41:03,336 --> 00:41:04,545
No!

659
00:41:04,629 --> 00:41:06,047
Words of power!

660
00:41:06,130 --> 00:41:08,800
Foul Carrionite spectres,

661
00:41:08,883 --> 00:41:11,803
cease your show, between the points...

662
00:41:13,221 --> 00:41:14,764
7-6-1-3-9-0!

663
00:41:15,056 --> 00:41:17,183
7-6-1-3-9-0!

664
00:41:17,600 --> 00:41:21,688
Banished like a tinker's cuss,
I say to thee...

665
00:41:24,273 --> 00:41:25,400
Uh...

666
00:41:25,984 --> 00:41:27,318
Expelliarmus!

667
00:41:27,402 --> 00:41:29,612
-Expelliarmus!
-Expelliarmus!

668
00:41:29,737 --> 00:41:31,322
Good old JK!

669
00:41:31,906 --> 00:41:33,574
(SHRIEKING)

670
00:41:35,660 --> 00:41:37,328
The deep darkness!

671
00:41:37,412 --> 00:41:39,580
They are consumed!

672
00:41:56,055 --> 00:41:58,891
Love's Labour's Won, there it goes.

673
00:42:08,818 --> 00:42:10,611
(AUDIENCE GASPING)

674
00:42:14,949 --> 00:42:17,076
(HESITANT APPLAUSE)

675
00:42:21,998 --> 00:42:24,625
(ALL CHEERING)

676
00:42:32,467 --> 00:42:34,677
They think it was all special effects?

677
00:42:34,802 --> 00:42:36,971
Your effect is special, indeed.

678
00:42:37,055 --> 00:42:39,182
It's not your best line.

679
00:42:55,656 --> 00:42:57,617
(SHRIEKING)

680
00:43:11,172 --> 00:43:12,757
And I say,

681
00:43:12,840 --> 00:43:16,094
a heart for a hart, a dear for a deer.

682
00:43:16,177 --> 00:43:19,806
-I don't get it.
-Then give me a joke from Freedonia.

683
00:43:19,931 --> 00:43:24,102
Okay, Shakespeare walks into a pub,
and the landlord says,

684
00:43:24,185 --> 00:43:26,145
"0}, mate, you're Bard."

685
00:43:26,229 --> 00:43:28,773
(LAUGHING) That's brilliant!

686
00:43:28,898 --> 00:43:31,651
Doesn't make sense, mind you,
but never mind that. Come here.

687
00:43:31,734 --> 00:43:33,152
I've only just met you.

688
00:43:33,236 --> 00:43:37,365
The Doctor may never kiss you.
Why not entertain a man who will?

689
00:43:39,158 --> 00:43:41,953
I don't know how to tell you this,
O Great Genius,

690
00:43:42,036 --> 00:43:44,372
but your breath doesn't half stink.

691
00:43:44,455 --> 00:43:47,166
Good prop store back there!

692
00:43:47,250 --> 00:43:49,669
I'm not sure about this, though.

693
00:43:49,752 --> 00:43:51,337
Reminds me of a Sycorax.

694
00:43:51,420 --> 00:43:55,133
Sycorax. Nice word.
I'll have that off you as well.

695
00:43:55,216 --> 00:43:58,094
-I should be on 10%. How's your head?
-Still aching.

696
00:43:58,219 --> 00:44:00,221
Here, I got you this.

697
00:44:01,139 --> 00:44:02,723
Neck brace.

698
00:44:03,391 --> 00:44:05,810
Wear that for a few days
until it's better.

699
00:44:05,893 --> 00:44:08,062
Although you might want to keep it,
it suits you.

700
00:44:08,146 --> 00:44:11,399
-What about the play?
-Gone. I looked all over.

701
00:44:11,524 --> 00:44:14,193
Every single copy of Love's Labour's Won
went up in the sky.

702
00:44:14,277 --> 00:44:17,613
-My lost masterpiece.
-You could write it up again.

703
00:44:17,697 --> 00:44:19,699
Yeah, better not, Will.

704
00:44:19,782 --> 00:44:22,994
There's still power in those words.
Maybe it should best stay forgotten.

705
00:44:23,077 --> 00:44:24,954
Oh, but I've got new ideas.

706
00:44:25,037 --> 00:44:27,665
Perhaps it's time
I wrote about fathers and sons,

707
00:44:27,748 --> 00:44:30,084
in memory of my boy, my precious Hamnet.

708
00:44:30,168 --> 00:44:31,919
-Hamnet?
-That's him.

709
00:44:32,044 --> 00:44:33,796
-Ham-net?
-What's wrong with that?

710
00:44:33,921 --> 00:44:35,923
Anyway, time we were off.

711
00:44:36,048 --> 00:44:38,050
I've got a nice attic in the Tardis

712
00:44:38,176 --> 00:44:40,595
where this lot
can scream for all eternity.

713
00:44:40,678 --> 00:44:43,097
And I've got to take
Martha back to Freedonia.

714
00:44:43,181 --> 00:44:46,017
You mean travel on
through time and space?

715
00:44:46,100 --> 00:44:47,185
You what?

716
00:44:47,268 --> 00:44:48,853
You're from another world,
like the Carrionites.

717
00:44:48,936 --> 00:44:51,772
And Martha here's from the future.
It's not hard to work out.

718
00:44:51,856 --> 00:44:55,026
That's incredible. You are incredible.

719
00:44:55,109 --> 00:44:57,904
We're alike in many ways, Doctor.

720
00:44:57,987 --> 00:45:01,616
Martha, let me say goodbye to you
with a new verse.

721
00:45:01,699 --> 00:45:03,868
A sonnet for my dark lady.

722
00:45:06,871 --> 00:45:09,207
Shall I compare thee to a summer's day?

723
00:45:09,290 --> 00:45:11,709
Thou art more lovely, more temperate...

724
00:45:11,792 --> 00:45:13,294
-Will!
-will!

725
00:45:13,377 --> 00:45:15,463
Will, you'll never believe it.
She's here!

726
00:45:15,546 --> 00:45:19,050
-She's turned up!
-We're the talk of the town.

727
00:45:19,133 --> 00:45:21,719
She heard about last night.
She wants us to perform it again.

728
00:45:21,802 --> 00:45:25,014
-Who?
-Her Majesty. She's here!

729
00:45:25,139 --> 00:45:27,558
(TRUMPETS HERALDING)

730
00:45:28,184 --> 00:45:30,186
Queen Elizabeth I!

731
00:45:30,311 --> 00:45:32,063
-Doctor!
-What?

732
00:45:32,146 --> 00:45:34,857
-My sworn enemy.
-What?

733
00:45:34,982 --> 00:45:36,734
Off with his head!

734
00:45:36,817 --> 00:45:39,320
-What?
-Well, never mind what, just run!

735
00:45:39,403 --> 00:45:41,072
-See you, Will. And thanks!
-Stop him!

736
00:45:41,155 --> 00:45:43,449
Stop that pernicious Doctor!

737
00:45:47,995 --> 00:45:50,748
Stop! In the name of the Queen!

738
00:45:50,831 --> 00:45:52,708
What have you done to upset her?

739
00:45:52,833 --> 00:45:55,544
How should I know? I haven't met
her yet! That's time travel for you.

740
00:45:55,628 --> 00:45:57,630
Still, I can't wait to find out.

741
00:45:57,713 --> 00:45:59,840
That's something to look forward to.

742
00:45:59,966 --> 00:46:01,342
Ooh!

743
00:46:06,847 --> 00:46:08,808
And we're slap-bang in the middle
of New New York.

744
00:46:08,891 --> 00:46:10,559
I am the last of my kind.

745
00:46:10,685 --> 00:46:11,978
Help us!

746
00:46:14,897 --> 00:46:16,857
You've got to let her go!

747
00:46:16,983 --> 00:46:18,651
Martha!

748
00:46:19,151 --> 00:46:21,028
I need to talk to the police.

749
00:46:23,030 --> 00:46:25,074
-Do you want some happy?
-Buy some anger!

750
00:46:25,199 --> 00:46:26,701
How much do you want forgetting?

751
00:46:26,826 --> 00:46:28,202
Pretty well dressed for a hitchhiker.

752
00:46:28,327 --> 00:46:30,955
They say people go missing
on the motorway.

753
00:46:31,038 --> 00:46:33,791
Some cars just vanish,
never to be seen again.

754
00:46:33,874 --> 00:46:36,294
Is there something living down there?

755
00:46:36,377 --> 00:46:38,129
What the hell are they?

